 racialized in Germany as temporary and migrant grunt workers, yet their middle-class aspirations reflect efforts to build a new, global, and economically dominant India. The ways they accept and resist the premises and conditions of their work offer new potentials for alternative visions of living and working in neoliberal economies. Demonstrating how these coders' cognitive labor realigns and reimagines race and class, Amrute conceptualizes personhood and migration within global capitalism in new ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aComputer programmersxGermanyxBerlin. 0aComputer programmersxIndia. 0aComputer programmerszGermanyzBerlin. 0aComputer programmerszIndia. 0aEast IndiansxGermanyxBerlin. 0aEast IndianszGermanyzBerlin. 0aForeign workers, East IndianxGermanyxBerlin. 0aForeign workers, East IndianzGermanyzBerlin. 0aInformation technologyxEmployeesxGermanyxBerlin. 0aInformation technologyzGermanyzBerlinxEmployees. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070808040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478091875zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478091875zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478091875/original  a978-3-11-070808-0 Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA